## Complexity Analysis
 
| Case | Time Complexity | Why? |
|------|----------------|------|
| Best | O(n log n) | Unsorted and uses can properly divide and conquer |
| Average | O(n log n) | simi sorted but can properly divide |
| Worst | O(n²) | Already sorted will pivot at lowest value recursing a big arrays of partitions |

## Reflection Questions

1. What happens if the array is already sorted and you always pick the first element as pivot?
- It’s worst case scenario as the list is sorted and we’re picking the lowest object in the list so everything will always be greater than the pivot in every recursion  

2. How could you improve pivot selection to avoid worst-case performance?
- A random or half-way pivot 

3. How does quicksort compare to other sorting algorithms you know (e.g., bubble sort, merge sort)?
- quicksort is fast since it doesn't hit as many worst case scenarios and is easy to implement 

4. Why do we use `array[1:]` instead of `array` when building the less and greater lists?
- It goes through elements 1- the end of the array and it's a good way to cut down on code size and improve efficiency and can preserve the original list

